Only contractors with appropriate ISO or otherrecognized quality system accreditation are to be employed.5.11.1EVALUATION, SELECTION AND APPROVAL OF CONTRACTORSIn order to obtain approval, a contractor is required to fill the HSE questionnaire TA 003 which will be reviewed by the TechnicalSuperintendent and approved by the General Manager.Amongst other factors the following shall be taken into consideration:Does the Contractor :a. Have safety management systems that include effective risk assessment, control of work, management of change, incidentinvestigation and environmental and emergency response systems.b. Have systems to provide suitable equipment that is maintained to a documented standard.c. Have systems to provide appropriately screened, trained, qualified and experienced personnel.d. Have a process for self-measurement, continuous improvement and reporting of agreed KPls to the company.e. Have a procedure for proactive reporting details of operational and safety performance.f. Have ISO 14001 certification.g. have adequate resources and systems in place to enable us to meet our environmental protection standards.A list of qualifed providers shall be maintained by the Technical Department. A Review of all the approved Contractors is tocarried out once in 4 years and the process is similar to that of approval.5.11.2PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENTS AND SCOPE OF WORKThe Performance Requirements and scope of Work is to be defined clearly to contractors and subcontractors and all parties shouldmeet with the arm of understanding the work scope, responsibilities and interfaces.Performance requirements include the contractor having standard operating procedures that are fully consistent with those of thecompany and incorporate HSE expectations. Where difference or gaps exist, they are be detailed in a bridging document.A feedback mechanism should be in place to ensure that the understanding of all parties, both ashore and on board, is aligned.5.11.3ROLES AND RESPONSIBILITIES AND BRIDGING DOCUMENTSPlans for project or technical requirements are to be jointly developed with the contractor.A bridging document should be in place prior to mobilisation to define roles and responsibilities for the operation and maintenance ofequipment and the applicability of HSE and management systems.Where a client appoints contractors, the roles and responsibilities of all parties are to be agreed and defined.5.11.4MONITORING AND ASSESSMENTThe company monitors and assesses the HSE and Technical performance of contractors and provides feedback to enable contractorsto address deficiencies and improve their management systems.6VESSEL MAINTENANCE AND TECHNICAL OPERATIONS6.1MAINTENANCE POLICYVessels shall be entered with a recognised classification society and shall be maintained and managed to high safety/ quality standards in accordance with the company policies, ISMCode, national and international regulations and industry standards (i.e. OCIMF, IMCA, OVID, OVMSA, CMID, etc.) and to the structural, operational and cosmetic conditionagreed with owners.The maintenance shall be carried out in the most cost-effective manner at the same time ensuring that vessels are seaworthy and cargo-worthy at all times as well as to minimize therisk of breakdown and resultant off-hire.Budgetary constraints should not compromise the supply of spares for safety of the vessel. In such cases the vessel’s Superintendent shall pro-actively interact with the owners andarrange for supply of necessary spares. Vessel’s shipboard management and the vessel’s technical superintendent shall ensure that the vessel has adequate spares for safe operation ofthe vessel especially the minimum spares as identified in the Phoenix Inventory Module.
